author: David Thompson
title: Win over Lumberton moves Ozen volleyball team to 3rd place
text:
Win over Lumberton moves Ozen volleyball team to 3rd place David Thompso , Beaumont Enterprise Published 9:42 am, Wednesday, October 21, 2015 
Brittanie Cockrell couldn't help but shed a few tears between hugs from her teammates. 
The Ozen senior celebrated her first career win over Lumberton Tuesday night during an emotional home match with deep playoff implications for both sides. 
The Lady Panthers needed all of Cockrell's match-high 15 kills to fend off Lumberton in five sets, 25-17, 21-25, 21-25, 25-20, 15-10. 
"I love this team so much, they are like my family," Cockrell said. "We have a lot of heart on this team and we were able to play smart enough to win the match. Sure we have a lot of athleticism, but you need brains to pull out something like this." 
The win moved Ozen (8-4) all alone into third place in District 22-5A while Lumberton (7-5) fell into a fourth-place tie with Port Neches-Groves (7-5). The Rock-A-Noos swept Baytown Lee Tuesday at home. 
Ozen can clinch a playoff spot Friday with a win over PN-G in their final home match of the season. 
"It would mean so much to be able to go to the playoff with this team," Cockrell said. "I wouldn't want to go with anyone else." 
Tempestt Vaughn , Alissa Johnson and Mercedes Perry all contributed at least six kills for the Lady Panthers, who fought back from a 2-1 set deficit for the win. Vaughn added a match-high four blocks. 
"Give Lumberton credit, they are a great team," said Ozen coach Stephanie March-Smith. "This was a battle and we were lucky to leave on top. This is a huge win for this program and the girls. They deserve to celebrate. They've worked hard for this moment. There is just still work to be done." 
Haley Hood and Taylor Kile led Lumberton in defeat, registering 13 and nine kills respectively. The Lady Raiders will face first-place Goose Creek Memorial Friday at home before hosting Central next Tuesday for their final regular season match.
